               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-227-person1878">
                  JAMES 
                  DRAKE
               <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1878" type="surname" value="DRAKE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1878" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1878" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18291029-227-crimeloc1288">Crispin-street, Spitalfields</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-227-crimeloc1288" type="placeName" value="Crispin-street, Spitalfields"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18291029-227-crimeloc1288" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-227-off1286 t18291029-227-crimeloc1288"></join>, in the parish of Christchurch, and am a <rs id="t18291029-227-viclabel1289" type="occupation">watch-gilder</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-227-victim1877 t18291029-227-viclabel1289"></join>; I keep the house. The prisoner came to me as a lodger on the 26th of September - he had one room on the second floor,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182910290090"></xptr>as a single man; I keep my watches in drawers on the ground floor. On the 30th of September, about two o'clock, I went to see what the time was, and found every thing correct in the drawer; I shut the drawer and the door of the room, but did not lock it - I saw the prisoner in the shop between four and five o'clock; he said he wanted to write a letter to send to Portsmouth, to his father - I <rs id="t18291029-227-viclabel1290" type="occupation">keep a chandler's-shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-227-victim1877 t18291029-227-viclabel1290"></join>; the watches were in my bed-room- the prisoner had slept at home every night till then, but did not on that night; I went to the drawer about half-past seven o'clock that evening, and missed two silver watches, they were fairly worth from 3l. to three guineas each, at least, and a chain to each watch - a gold mourning-ring, worth from 38s., to 2l. - I gave 38s. for it at a jeweller's shop; it weighed 5 1/2 dwts., and a seal worth 10s.; in consequence of the prisoner saying he was writing to his father at Portsmouth. I went down there about the 17th or 18th of October, and found him at his father's house: I gave him into custody, and had him brought here - (looking at a watch produced by Wild) this is one of the watches I lost, and the chain to it; I have had the watch about eighteen months; I am not the maker - it is my own gilding; I am quite sure of it - there is no maker's name on it; it was in this state when I lost it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-227-person1879">
                  ROBERT 
                  WILD
               <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1879" type="surname" value="WILD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1879" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1879" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Mr. Sowerby, a pawnbroker, of Chiswell-street. I received this watch in pawn from the prisoner on the 30th of September, between seven and eight o'clock in the evening, and lent him 30s. on it; I never saw him before, but am quite certain of his person - I gave him what I supposed amounted to 30s.; he came next morning, and said I had given him a 7s. piece instead of a half-sovereign - I said, "I gave it you for the watch you pawned last night, did not I?" he said Yes, and I gave him half a sovereign for it - I am quite certain of him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-227-person1880">
                  JOSHUA 
                  ARMSTRONG
               <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1880" type="surname" value="ARMSTRONG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1880" type="given" value="JOSHUA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-227-person1880" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of Worship-street. I went to Portsmouth, and took the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Armstrong knows my character. Witness. His father has been forty-two years in His Majesty's dockyard at Portsmouth, and has been a very respectable man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. My friends are all at Portsmouth.</p>
